From a full consideration of the various passages in which he allodes to, or discusses the question, l am of opinion that Bacon, while adopt· ing the atomic theory as to the ultimate constitution of matter, rejected the vacuum by which the minute particles were supposed to be separated, as well as the eternal, rigid and anchangeable character ascribed to the particles or atoms themselves. Hence the varying terms in which he speaks of Democritus. See my notes on i. 63, ii. 8 ad init, ii 48 (a), and ii. 48 (conclusion).
